                    name="Custom Title"
                    title="The future of patient safety"
                    titleType="h2"/>
                <block_10
                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                    sling:resourceType="core/franklin/components/block/v1/block"
                    analytics_id="-"
                    blockId="-"
                    classes_customDynamicClass="spacing-bottom,width-large"
                    filter="text-container"
                    language="none"
                    model="text-container"
                    modelFields="[classes_customDynamicClass,blockId,classes_commonCustomClass,language,analytics_id]"
                    name="Text Container">
                    <item_0
                        jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                        sling:resourceType="core/franklin/components/block/v1/block/item"
                        model="text-container-text"
                        modelFields="[text]"
                        name="Text Container Text"
                        text="&lt;p>A laser focus on patients is emphasized within the growing field of precision medicine, which is intertwined with patient safety, Lievano says.&lt;/p>&lt;p>“The future is precision pharmacovigilance, where you’ll take medicine based on your DNA,” he says. “As an industry, we’ll rely on genomics and take it to the point where we can predict what will happen in the body.”&lt;/p>&lt;p>Precision pharmacovigilance is just one important area within safety science around the globe, illustrating the need for a future-looking approach driven by what’s best for patients, Scarazzini says.&lt;/p>&lt;p>“We built our pharmacovigilance team around data science and patient insights, relying on evidence and the strong voices of patients to bring us into the future,” she says.&lt;/p>"/>
                </block_10>
